{"bare_answer": "## Gas on Mantle Network\n\n### Token Required\nYou need **MNT** (Mantle's native token) to pay for gas fees on the Mantle network.\n\n---\n\n### Common Assumption to Avoid\n❌ **Don't assume you need ETH for gas.**\n\nMany developers and users coming from Ethereum or other EVM-compatible chains automatically assume ETH is the gas token (as it is on Ethereum, Arbitrum, Optimism, etc.). Mantle is EVM-compatible, but it uses **MNT** — not ETH — as its native gas token.\n\n---\n\n### Practical Implication\n- When bridging to Mantle or setting up a wallet, make sure you have **MNT** for transactions, not just ETH or other tokens.\n- If you arrive on Mantle with only ETH (bridged), you may find yourself **unable to execute transactions** because you lack the native gas token.", "with_skill_answer": "## Gas on Mantle\n\n**Gas token: `MNT`**\n\nYou pay gas fees on Mantle using **MNT**, not ETH.\n\n### Common Assumption to Avoid\n\n**Do not assume an ETH-funded wallet can transact on Mantle.** This is a frequent mistake developers make when coming from mainnet Ethereum or other EVM chains. Even though Mantle is Ethereum-aligned, your wallet needs **MNT** to cover gas — an ETH balance alone won't be enough to send transactions.\n\n### Practical Takeaway\nWhen onboarding users or setting up wallets for Mantle, always ensure they have MNT funded, not just ETH. This affects:\n- **Deploying contracts**\n- **Sending transactions**\n- **Any on-chain interaction**\n\nCheck the official Mantle documentation and onboarding tools for current bridging and faucet options to acquire MNT, as ecosystem tooling details can change over time.", "skill_found": true, "question_id": "MANTLE-Q25", "category": "Mantle", "skill_id": "mantle/mantle-network-primer", "ground_truth": "MNT is the gas token on Mantle. Developers should not assume ETH-funded wallets can transact on Mantle.", "question_text": "What token do I need to pay gas on Mantle, and what common assumption should I av