{"bare_answer": "## Mantle Transaction Finality\n\nNo, a transaction appearing in an L2 block is **not fully final** at that point. Mantle (like other Optimistic Rollup systems) has a multi-stage finality model.\n\n---\n\n## Finality Stages\n\n### 1. **Unsafe / Pending** (immediate)\n- Transaction is received by the sequencer\n- Included in an L2 block\n- Fast but offers **no guarantees** — the sequencer could theoretically reorg or censor\n\n### 2. **Safe / Soft Finality**\n- Transaction data is **posted (batched) to Ethereum L1** as calldata/blobs\n- The L2 state is now anchored to L1\n- Much stronger guarantee, but still not fully final\n\n### 3. **Finalized / Hard Finality**\n- The **challenge window expires** (typically **7 days** for Optimistic Rollups)\n- During this window, anyone can submit a **fraud proof** disputing the state root\n- Only after this window closes without a successful challenge is the state considered **fully and irreversibly final** on L1\n\n---\n\n## Practical Implications\n\n| Stage | Time | Risk Level |\n|-------|------|------------|\n| L2 block inclusion | Seconds | Sequencer trust required |\n| Batch posted to L1 | Minutes–hours | Data availability secured |\n| Challenge window closed | ~7 days | Fully final |\n\n---\n\n## Key Takeaway\n\n> Full finality requires waiting out the **fraud proof challenge period** (~7 days). Most applications treat L2 block inclusion as *practically* final for everyday use, but **withdrawals to L1** require waiting the full challenge window.", "with_skill_answer": "## Transaction Finality on Mantle\n\n**No** — appearing in an L2 block means the transaction has been **included**, but it is not yet **fully final**.\n\nHere's the distinction:\n\n### Inclusion vs. Finality\n\n| Stage | What It Means | Final? |\n|---|---|---|\n| **L2 Block Inclusion** | The **sequencer** has ordered and included your transaction in an L2 block | ❌ No |\n| **L1 Settlement** | Transaction data is posted and verified on Ethereum L1 | ✅ Yes (finalized) |\n\n### Why the Difference Matters\n\n- The **sequencer** is the component that orders and produces L2 blocks. At this stage, the transaction is visible and typically reliable for most practical purposes, but it depends on the sequencer's continued honest operation.\n- **Settlement** is the process by which L2 state is committed to Ethereum L1, inheriting Ethereum's security guarantees. Only after this step is a transaction considered **fully and trustlessly final**.\n- **Finality** therefore refers to the point at which a transaction is irreversible and cryptographically anchored to L1 — not merely when it appears on L2.\n\n### Practical Takeaway\n\n- For **low-value or time-sensitive UX**, L2 inclusion is often treated as \"soft confirmation.\"\n- For **high-value transfers, bridging, or cross-chain operations**, you should wait for **L1 settlement** before considering funds fully secured.\n\n> ⚠️ For current settlement times or live chain status, this document alone is insufficient — a live source check is recommended.", "skill_found": true, "question_id": "MANTLE-Q28", "category": "Mantle", "skill_id": "mantle/mantle-network-primer", "ground_truth": "L2 inclusion is not the same as L1-backed settlement/finality. A transaction being visible in an L2 block does not mean the strongest settlement assurance has been reached.", "question_text": "Is a Mantle transaction fully final once it appears in an L2 block?", "provider": "anthropic/claude-sonnet-4-6"}
{"bare_answer": "## Mantle Public RPC for Production Use\n\n**Short answer: No, it is not recommended for production or high-frequency traffic.**\n\n### Why Not\n\nThe official public Mantle RPC endpoints (e.g., `https://rpc.mantle.xyz`) are:\n\n- **Rate limited** — requests will be throttled or rejected under heavy load\n- **Shared infrastructure** — used by many developers simultaneously\n- **No SLA guarantees** — no uptime or latency commitments\n- **Unreliable for high-frequency calls** — will drop requests under sustained load\n- **Not suitable for WebSocket subscriptions** at scale\n\n### Better Alternatives for Production\n\n| Option | Examples |\n|--------|---------|\n| **Dedicated RPC providers** | Alchemy, QuickNode, Ankr, Blast API |\n| **Self-hosted node** | Run your own Mantle node |\n| **Enterprise endpoints** | Provider-specific paid plans with SLAs |\n\n### Recommended Approach\n\n```\nDevelopment/Testing  →  Public RPC is fine\nProduction/High Traffic  →  Use a dedicated provider or self-hosted node\n```\n\n### Practical Guidance\n\n- Use public RPC only for **prototyping or low-traffic scenarios**\n- Implement **fallback RPC logic** even with paid providers\n- Monitor **rate limit errors** (429 responses) as a signal to upgrade\n\nThe public RPC is intentionally a convenience endpoint, not a production-grade service.", "with_skill_answer": "## Public Mantle RPC for Production Use\n\n### Stable Concept\n\nMantle's public RPC endpoints are provided for convenience — typically for development, testing, and low-frequency use. Like most L2 public RPCs, they are **rate-limited**, meaning they will throttle or reject requests beyond certain thresholds.\n\n---\n\n### Developer Guidance\n\n**No — the public RPC is not recommended as a default for production or high-frequency traffic.**\n\nKey reasons:\n\n- **Rate limits apply**, which can cause failed or dropped requests under load\n- **No SLA guarantees** — uptime and latency are not contractually backed on public endpoints\n- **Shared infrastructure** — you compete with all other users hitting the same endpoint\n\n---\n\n### What to Use Instead\n\nFor production or high-frequency workloads, you should use a **dedicated node provider**. Mantle is supported by third-party RPC providers (e.g., Alchemy, Ankr, Blast, QuickNode, and others). Check the current list here:\n\n> 📎 **https://docs.mantle.xyz/network/for-developers/resources-and-tooling/node-endpoints-and-providers**\n\n---\n\n### ⚠️ Live-Verify Note\n\nThe specific provider list, rate limit thresholds, and availability of free vs. paid tiers **change over time**. Always confirm current options and limits from the official docs link above before making infrastructure decisions.", "skill_found": true, "question_id": "MANTLE-Q30", "category": "Mantle", "skill_id": "mantle/mantle-network-primer", "ground_truth": "Official public Mantle RPC endpoints are rate-limited. Production or high-frequency workloads should use a dedicated provider.", "question_text": "Is the official public Mantle RPC a good default for production or high-frequency traffic?", "provider": "anthropic/claude-sonnet-4-6"}
