pe-determination steps are complete should the mandatory data-fetching steps (4 onward) begin.", "skill_found": true, "question_id": "MANTLE-Q39", "category": "Mantle", "skill_id": "mantle/mantle-portfolio-analyst", "ground_truth": "Use mantle_validateAddress before the read-only queries. Validate wallet, token, and spender addresses instead of guessing. If addresses are invalid, the workflow should not proceed as if they were trusted.", "question_text": "What should happen before querying a wallet, token, or spender address in the portfolio analyst?", "provider": "anthropic/claude-sonnet-4-6"}
{"bare_answer": "HTTP status code 429 indicates \"Too Many Requests.\" This means that the client has sent too many requests in a given amount of time, and the server is limiting the rate at which requests can be processed. This is often implemented to prevent abuse or overloading of the server.\n\nHere are some steps you can take to address this issue:\n\n1. **Check Rate Limits**: Review the documentation for the Mantle RPC service to understand its rate limits. This will give you an idea of how many requests you can send in a specific timeframe.\n\n2. **Implement Backoff Strategy**: If you receive a 429 response, implement an exponential backoff strategy in your application. This means that after receiving a 429, you should wait for a certain period before retrying the request, increasing the wait time with each subsequent failure.\n\n3. **Reduce Request Frequency**: If possible, reduce the frequency of your requests. This may involve batching requests or optimizing your application's logic to make fewer calls.\n\n4. **Monitor Usage**: Keep track of your request usage over time to ensure you stay within the allowed limits. This can help you avoid hitting the rate limit in the future.\n\n5. **Contact Support**: If you believe you are receiving this error in error or if you need higher rate limits, consider reaching out to the support team for the Mantle RPC service for assistance.\n\n6. **Check for Errors in Code**: Ensure that your application is not unintentionally sending excessive requests due to bugs or misconfigurations.\n\nBy following these steps, you should be able to manage the 429 responses effectively and adjust your application's behavior accordingly.", "with_skill_answer": "HTTP 429 indicates that the client has sent too many requests in a given amount of time, which is often referred to as \"Too Many Requests.\" This typically means that you have exceeded the rate limits set by the Mantle RPC service.\n\nHere’s what you should do next:\n\n1. **Capture Failure Context**:\n   - Note the method/tool name you were using.\n   - Record the endpoint you were trying to access.\n   - Document the parameters you sent with the request.\n   - Take note of the timestamp (UTC) when the error occurred.\n   - Capture the full error text/code (in this case, HTTP 429).\n\n2. **Classify the Error**:\n   - This error falls under the category of RPC transport/connectivity issues, specifically related to rate limiting.\n\n3. **Run Targeted Checks**:\n   - Review the rate limits specified in the Mantle RPC documentation to understand the maximum number of requests allowed.\n   - Consider implementing exponential backoff in your request logic to avoid hitting the rate limit.\n\n4. **Return Root-Cause Hypothesis**:\n   - The root cause is likely due to exceeding the rate limit for the RPC service. The immediate next step is to reduce the frequency of your requests or implement a retry mechanism with backoff.\n\n5. **If Unresolved**:\n   - If the issue persists after adjusting your request frequency, consider escalating the issue by checking the following:\n     - Confirm if there are any ongoing issues with the Mantle RPC service.\n     - Review your application’s request patterns to identify any potential optimizations.\n     - Reach out to the Mantle support team for further assistance if necessary. \n\nBy following these steps, you can effectively address the HTTP 429 error and ensure smoother interactions with the Mantle RPC service.", "skill_found": true, "question_id": "MANTLE-Q41", "category": "Mantle", "skill_id": "mantle/mantle-readonly-debugger", "ground_truth": "HTTP 429 indicates rate limiting or provider saturation. Reduce request rate, retry with backoff, or switch to a fallback endpoint. Production workloads should prefer dedicated providers over public RPC.", "question_text": "Mantle RPC is returning HTTP 429. What does that usually mean and what should I do next?", "provider": "openai/gpt-4o-mini"}
{"bare_answer": "## Mantle RPC Call Timeout\n\n### Issue Type\nThis is a **Network/Connectivity Issue** (or **RPC Infrastructure Issue**), specifically a **timeout error** — meaning your client sent a request to the Mantle RPC endpoint but did not receive a response within the expected time window.\n\n---\n\n### First Thing To Do\n\n**Check the status of the Mantle RPC endpoint / network.**\n\nSpecifically:\n1. **Visit the Mantle network status page** or check their official channels (Discord, Twitter) for any ongoing outages or degraded performance\n2. **Verify your RPC endpoint URL** is correct and still active\n3. **Try an alternative RPC endpoint** to rule out a provider-specific issue\n\n---\n\n### Why This First?\nBefore debugging your code or configuration, you need to confirm whether the problem is **on your end or the network's end**. If the RPC provider is down or congested, no amount of local debugging will fix it.\n\n---\n\n### After That, If the Network Looks Fine:\n- Check your **internet connection**\n- Increase your **timeout threshold** in your RPC client config\n- Check for **rate limiting** on your RPC provider\n- Retry with **exponential backoff**\n- Switch to a dedicated RPC provider (e.g., Alchemy, Blast, QuickNode for Mantle)", "with_skill_answer": "## Classification\n\nBased on the error signature map, an RPC call timeout falls under:\n\n**Issue Type: `RPC transport/connectivity`**\n\n---\n\n## Immediate First Steps\n\nFollowing the troubleshooting playbook for transport/connectivity failures:\n\n### 1. Verify Endpoint Health\n- Confirm the RPC endpoint is reachable (ping / HTTP HEAD check)\n- Check the Mantle network status page for active incidents\n- Validate your endpoint URL is correct (mainnet vs. testnet)\n\n### 2. Check Request Parameters\n- **Timeout threshold** — is your client timeout too aggressive? (recommend ≥ 30s for archive/trace calls)\n- **Block range** — overly wide `eth_getLogs` or similar range queries are a common cause of gateway timeouts\n- **Method complexity** — calls like `debug_traceTransaction` or large `eth_call` simulations can exceed server limits\n\n### 3. Retry with Backoff\n```\nAttempt 1 → immediate retry\nAttempt 2 → 2s delay\nAttempt 3 → 5s delay\n→ If still failing, rotate to a fallback RPC endpoint\n```\n\n### 4. Isolate the Failure\n- Try the **same call on a secondary endpoint** to determine if it's endpoint-specific or network-wide\n- Try a **lightweight call** (`eth_blockNumber`) on the same endpoint to confirm basic connectivity\n\n---\n\n## Root-Cause Hypothesis\n\n| Hypothesis | Confidence |\n|---|---|\n| Endpoint overloaded or rate-limiting | High |\n| Query scope too large (block range / data size) | Medium |\n| Network-level incident on Mantle | Low–Medium |\n\n---\n\n## Escalation Checklist (if unresolved)\n\n- [ ] Confirmed failure on **multiple endpoints**?\n- [ ] Captured full request payload and response headers?\n- [ ] Checked Mantle Discord / status page for known outages?\n- [ ] Narrowed block range or simplified the query?\n- [ ] Reported to RPC provider with timestamp + method name?", "skill_found": true, "question_id": "MANTLE-Q40", "category": "Mantle", "skill_id": "mantle/mantle-readonly-debugger", "ground_truth": "A timeout is a transport or connectivity problem, not automatically a contract bug. Check endpoint health or rate-limit signals. Retry with bounded backoff and compare endpoints if needed.", "question_text": "A Mantle RPC call timed out. What issue type is that and what should I do first?", "provider": "anthropic/claude-sonnet-4-6"}
{"bare_answer": "When a quote call returns null or an error, the readonly debugger should follow a systematic approach to triage the issue. Here are the steps to consider:\n\n1. **Check Input Parameters**:\n   - Verify that the parameters being passed to the quote call are valid and correctly formatted. This includes checking for any required fields that may be missing.\n\n2. **Inspect Error Messages**:\n   - If an error is returned, examine the error message carefully. It may provide clues about what went wrong, such as invalid input, authentication issues, or service unavailability.\n\n3. **Review API Documentation**:\n   - Consult the API documentation for the quote service to ensure that the call is being made correctly. Look for any changes in the API that might affect the call.\n\n4. **Network Issues**:\n   - Check for any network connectivity issues that could prevent the call from reaching the service. This includes checking firewalls, proxies, and other network configurations.\n\n5. **Service Status**:\n   - Verify the status of the quote service. It may be down for maintenance or experiencing outages. This can often be checked on the service provider's status page.\n\n6. **Rate Limiting**:\n   - Determine if the application has hit any rate limits imposed by the API. If so, the service may return null or an error until the limit resets.\n\n7. **Debugging Logs**:\n   - Review any available logs for additional context around the failure. This can include application logs, server logs, or any logging provided by the API.\n\n8. **Test with Known Values**:\n   - If possible, test the quote call with known good values to see if it returns a valid response. This can help isolate whether the issue is with specific input data.\n\n9. **Environment Consistency**:\n   - Ensure that the environment in which the debugger is running is consistent with the environment where the quote call is known to work. Differences in configuration or versions can lead to unexpected behavior.\n\n10. **Consult with Team**:\n    - If the issue persists, consult with team members or stakeholders who may have encountered similar issues or have insights into the service.\n\nBy following these steps, the readonly debugger can systematically identify and resolve the issue causing the quote call to return null or an error.", "with_skill_answer": "When a quote call returns null or an error, you should follow these steps using the Mantle Readonly Debugger workflow:\n\n1. **Capture Failure Context:**\n   - Note the method/tool name used for the quote call.\n   - Record the endpoint that was called.\n   - Document the parameters that were passed in the request.\n   - Capture the timestamp (UTC) when the error occurred.\n   - Collect the full error text or code that was returned.\n\n2. **Classify Error:**\n   - Based on the information gathered, classify the error using the `references/error-signature-map.md`. Since the issue involves a quote call returning null or an error, it likely falls under the category of \"quote/liquidity failure.\"\n\n3. **Run Targeted Checks:**\n   - Refer to `references/troubleshooting-playbook.md` to perform targeted checks related to quote failures. This may include checking for liquidity availability, verifying the parameters used in the quote call, or ensuring that the endpoint is functioning correctly.\n\n4. **Return Root-Cause Hypothesis:**\n   - After running the checks, formulate a root-cause hypothesis with a confidence level based on your findings. Provide an immediate next step based on this hypothesis, such as retrying the request with adjusted parameters or checking the liquidity status.\n\n5. **If Unresolved, Return Bounded Escalation Checklist:**\n   - If the issue remains unresolved after your checks and hypothesis, prepare a bounded escalation checklist that outlines the steps taken, the findings, and any additional information that may help in further diagnosing the issue.\n\nBy following this structured approach, you can effectively triage the issue with the quote call and work towards a resolution.", "skill_found": true, "question_id": "MANTLE-Q42", "category": "Mantle", "skill_id": "mantle/mantle-readonly-debugger", "ground_truth": "Classify this as a quote or liquidity failure. Verify token addresses, decimals, and amount scaling. Try a smaller size or an alternate route or source.", "question_text": "A quote call returns null or an error. How should the readonly debugger triage that?", "provider": "openai/gpt-4o-mini"}
