response times, throughput, and resource utilization.\n\n6. **User Impact**: Documentation of how the issue affects users, including any complaints or feedback received.\n\n7. **Visual Aids**: Screenshots, graphs, or charts that illustrate the problem or its impact can be helpful.\n\nBy providing this evidence, you can help the escalation team understand the severity and context of the issue, leading to a more efficient resolution process.", "with_skill_answer": "Mantle read-path debugging should be escalated when you encounter persistent issues that cannot be resolved through standard troubleshooting steps. This includes situations where:\n\n1. **Read-path requests consistently fail**.\n2. **Quotes revert** and cannot be successfully executed.\n3. **Balances disagree** between expected and actual values.\n4. **RPC behavior is inconsistent**, leading to unreliable responses.\n\nWhen escalating, it is important to include the following evidence:\n\n- Detailed logs of the requests that failed, including timestamps and error messages.\n- Specific examples of quotes that reverted, including the parameters used.\n- A comparison of expected versus actual balances, highlighting discrepancies.\n- Any patterns observed in the inconsistent RPC behavior, such as specific endpoints or times of day when issues occur.\n- Steps already taken during initial troubleshooting to provide context for the escalation.\n\nThis structured evidence will help in diagnosing the root cause of the issues more effectively.", "skill_found": true, "question_id": "MANTLE-Q45", "category": "Mantle", "skill_id": "mantle/mantle-readonly-debugger", "ground_truth": "Escalate when the issue remains unresolved after bounded retries and targeted checks. Include raw error strings, endpoints tested, request fingerprints, timestamped observations, and what was ruled out.", "question_text": "When should Mantle read-path debugging be escalated, and what evidence should be included?", "provider": "openai/gpt-4o-mini"}
{"bare_answer": "## Debugging an \"Execution Reverted\" Error on a Mantle Read Call\n\nAn **\"execution reverted\"** error on a **read call** (i.e., `eth_call`) is somewhat unusual since read calls don't consume gas or change state — but they can still revert. Here's what a debugger should do:\n\n---\n\n### 1. **Capture the Full Error Details**\n- Extract the **revert reason string** if present:\n  - ABI-decoded `Error(string)` → `0x08c379a0`\n  - Custom error selector → first 4 bytes of revert data\n  - `Panic(uint256)` → `0x4e487b71`\n- If the revert data is **empty**, note that separately — it means a bare `revert()` or `require(false)` with no message\n\n---\n\n### 2. **Identify the Revert Source**\nCheck whether the revert originated from:\n| Source | Likely Cause |\n|---|---|\n| **Contract logic** | `require()`, `revert`, failed assertion |\n| **Mantle node** | Block/state not available, RPC issue |\n| **Gas limit on `eth_call`** | Call ran out of gas even as a read |\n\n---\n\n### 3. **Inspect the Call Parameters**\n- Verify the **contract address** is correct and deployed on Mantle\n- Verify the **function selector** and **ABI encoding** of inputs\n- Check if the call is being made against the **correct block number** (stale state?)\n- Confirm the **`from` address** (some view functions check `msg.sender`)\n\n---\n\n### 4. **Simulate with More Detail**\n```bash\n# Use debug_traceCall if the Mantle node supports it\ncast call <contract> \"<function_sig>\" <args> \\\n  --rpc-url <mantle_rpc> \\\n  --trace\n```\nOr use `debug_traceCall` directly to get an **opcode-level trace** showing exactly where the revert happened.\n\n---\n\n### 5. **Common Mantle-Specific Considerations**\n- **MNT gas token**: Ensure gas-related logic isn't behaving differently than expected\n- **L2 state sync**: If reading cross-chain state, it may not be finalized yet\n- **Node version**: Mantle nodes may have quirks in `eth_call` handling — try a different RPC endpoint\n\n---\n\n### 6. **Resolution Checklist**\n- [ ] Decode revert reason\n- [ ] Confirm contract is deployed and not self-destructed\n- [ ] Validate ABI and input encoding\n- [ ] Check if a precondition in the function isn't met (e.g., paused contract, wrong role)\n- [ ] Try calling at a different block height\n- [ ] Test against a known-good RPC endpoint\n\n---\n\n### Key Takeaway\n> A reverted read call almost always means **the contract's own logic rejected the call** — treat it like a failed `require()` and work backward from the revert reason to find the unmet condition.", "with_skill_answer": "## Mantle Readonly Debugger — Handling \"execution reverted\" on a Read Call\n\nBased on the documented workflow and guardrails, here is exactly what the debugger does, step by step:\n\n---\n\n### Step 1 — Capture Failure Context\n\nThe debugger first collects and preserves all available details:\n\n| Field | What to Capture |\n|---|---|\n| `method` | The RPC method or tool name (e.g., `eth_call`) |\n| `endpoint` | The RPC URL used |\n| `parameters` | Full call params (contract address, calldata, block tag) |\n| `timestamp` | UTC time of the failure |\n| `raw_error` | **Verbatim** error string — e.g., `\"execution reverted\"` or `\"execution reverted: <reason>\"` — copied exactly, never paraphrased |\n\n> **Guardrail applied:** The original error string is preserved verbatim in `raw_error`. No summarizing or paraphrasing.\n\n---\n\n### Step 2 — Classify the Error\n\nUsing the **error-signature-map**, `\"execution reverted\"` on a read call maps to:\n\n- **Category:** Onchain revert or call exception\n- This is distinct from an RPC transport/connectivity issue — the request *reached the node* and the EVM itself rejected the execution.\n\n---\n\n### Step 3 — Run Targeted Checks (Read-Only)\n\nFrom the **troubleshooting-playbook**, the debugger runs the smallest reversible diagnostic steps first:\n\n1. **Check for a revert reason string** — does the error include a message after `\"execution reverted:\"` (e.g., a Solidity `require` message or custom error selector)?\n2. **Replay the call at a specific block** — use a pinned block tag instead of `\"latest\"` to rule out state race conditions.\n3. **Verify call parameters** — confirm the target address is a contract, calldata is correctly ABI-encoded, and the `from` address (if any) has no access restrictions.\n4. **Check contract state preconditions** — e.g., is the contract paused, is a required role missing, or is a view function dependent on state that doesn't exist yet?\n5. **Cross-check against a secondary RPC endpoint** — to rule out node-specific state inconsistency.\n\n> **Guardrail applied:** All steps remain **read-only** unless the user explicitly requests execution.\n\n---\n\n### Step 4 — Return Root-Cause Hypothesis\n\nThe debugger returns a structured result, for example:\n\n```\nhypothesis:    Contract-level revert — a require/revert condition was triggered during the static call.\nconfidence:    Medium (pending revert reason and parameter verification)\nimmediate_next_step: Re-run the call with full ABI decoding enabled to extract the revert reason string.\n```\n\n---\n\n### Step 5 — Escalation (If Unresolved)\n\nIf the above steps don't resolve it, the debugger returns a **bounded escalation checklist**:\n\n- [ ] Provide the full revert reason or custom error selector\n- [ ] Confirm the contract ABI matches the deployed bytecode\n- [ ] Share the exact calldata sent\n- [ ] Confirm which block/state the call was made against\n- [ ] Test against Mantle's canonical RPC endpoint to isolate node issues\n\n---\n\n**Key principle throughout:** No definitive root cause is claimed without", "skill_found": true, "question_id": "MANTLE-Q44", "category": "Mantle", "skill_id": "mantle/mantle-readonly-debugger", "ground_truth": "Classify this as a call or revert error. Verify the target address and ABI or function selector. Decode revert data if available and check inputs or state preconditions.", "question_text": "I got an \"execution reverted\" error from a Mantle read call. What should the debugger do?", "provider": "anthropic/claude-sonnet-4-6"}
{"bare_answer": "# Debugging Inconsistent Mantle Wallet Balance Reads\n\n## Root Causes to Investigate\n\n### 1. **RPC Node Inconsistency**\n```javascript\n// Problem: Different nodes return different states\nconst provider = new ethers.JsonRpcProvider(\"https://rpc.mantle.xyz\");\n\n// Debug: Check which block each read returns\nasync function debugBalance(address) {\n  const balance = await provider.getBalance(address);\n  const blockNumber = await provider.getBlockNumber();\n  console.log(`Balance: ${balance} at block: ${blockNumber}`);\n}\n```\n\n**Check:**\n- Are you hitting **load-balanced endpoints** returning different nodes?\n- Node sync lag between replicas\n\n---\n\n### 2. **Block Tag Specification**\n```javascript\n// Ambiguous - defaults to \"latest\" which varies\nconst balance = await provider.getBalance(address);\n\n// Explicit - pin to specific block\nconst balance = await provider.getBalance(address, \"finalized\");\nconst balance = await provider.getBalance(address, blockNumber);\n\n// Mantle block tags:\n// \"latest\"    → newest block (can vary across nodes)\n// \"safe\"      → unlikely to be reorged\n// \"finalized\" → fully confirmed\n// \"pending\"   → includes mempool (most volatile)\n```\n\n---\n\n### 3. **L2 Sequencer State vs L1 State**\n```javascript\n// Mantle-specific: L2 state may not match L1 bridge state\nasync function checkBothLayers(address) {\n  // L2 balance (Mantle)\n  const l2Provider = new ethers.JsonRpcProvider(\"https://rpc.mantle.xyz\");\n  const l2Balance = await l2Provider.getBalance(address);\n  \n  // L1 bridge balance (Ethereum)\n  const l1Provider = new ethers.JsonRpcProvider(\"https://eth-mainnet.rpc\");\n  // Check bridge contract for pending withdrawals\n  const bridgeContract = new ethers.Contract(BRIDGE_ADDRESS, BRIDGE_ABI, l1Provider);\n  const pendingWithdrawal = await bridgeContract.pendingWithdrawals(address);\n  \n  console.log({ l2Balance, pendingWithdrawal });\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### 4. **Race Conditions in Code**\n```javascript\n// BAD: Parallel reads may hit different states\nconst [bal1, bal2] = await Promise.all([\n  provider.getBalance(address),\n  provider.getBalance(address)\n]);\n\n// BETTER: Sequential reads at same block\nasync function consistentRead(address) {\n  const blockNumber = await provider.getBlockNumber();\n  const balance = await provider.getBalance(address, blockNumber);\n  return { balance, blockNumber };\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### 5. **Caching Layer Issues**\n```javascript\n// Check if middleware/SDK is caching stale data\n// ethers.js has built-in caching - inspect it\nprovider._cache  // check cached responses\n\n// Force fresh read\nprovider.cache?.clear?.();\n\n// Or use polling with explicit cache bypass\nprovider.pollingInterval = 1000; // ms\n```\n\n---\n\n## Systematic Debugging Checklist\n\n```javascript\nasync function fullDiagnostic(address) {\n  const results = {};\n  \n  //", "with_skill_answer": "Based on the **Mantle Readonly Debugger** workflow, here is the structured triage for a **balance inconsistency** issue:\n\n---\n\n## 1. Capture Failure Context\n\nBefore any checks, collect:\n\n| Field | What to Record |\n|---|---|\n| **Method/Tool** | e.g., `eth_getBalance`, SDK balance call |\n| **Endpoint** | RPC URL(s) being queried |\n| **Parameters** | Wallet address, block tag (`latest`, `pending`, specific block) |\n| **Timestamp (UTC)** | Time of each differing read |\n| **Error Text** | Exact values returned on each read |\n\n---\n\n## 2. Classify the Error\n\nPer `references/error-signature-map.md`, this maps to:\n\n> **Balance/Nonce Inconsistency** — repeated reads of the same address return different values without an intervening transaction.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Targeted Checks (from `references/troubleshooting-playbook.md`)\n\nThe debugger should run these checks in order:\n\n### 🔁 Block Tag Consistency\n- Are both reads using the **same block tag**?\n- `latest` can differ across nodes; prefer a **specific block number** to isolate the variable.\n\n### 🌐 RPC Node Consistency\n- Are reads hitting the **same RPC endpoint**? Load balancers may route to nodes at different sync heights.\n- Test by pinning to a single node URL and repeating both reads.\n\n### 📦 Node Sync State\n- Check if the RPC node is **fully synced** — a lagging node returns stale balances.\n- Call `eth_syncing`; if it returns a sync object (not `false`), the node is behind.\n\n### ⏱️ Pending Transactions\n- Is a **pending transaction** affecting balance between reads?\n- Compare `latest` vs. `pending` block tags to detect in-flight state.\n\n### 🔗 Chain Reorganization\n- Was there a **recent reorg** near the block of the first read?\n- Check block finality depth; on Mantle, confirm the block is past the finalization threshold.\n\n### 🧩 Caching Layer\n- Is there a **middleware cache** (e.g., proxy, SDK cache) returning a stale value?\n- Bypass any cache and query the RPC directly.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Root-Cause Hypothesis\n\n| Hypothesis | Confidence Trigger |\n|---|---|\n| **Different block tags used** | High — most common cause |\n| **Load-balanced RPC with sync skew** | High — if endpoint is a cluster |\n| **Pending tx in mempool** | Medium — if activity on the address is recent |\n| **Node not fully synced** | Medium — if `eth_syncing` ≠ `false` |\n| **Reorg on recent block** | Low-Medium — if block depth is shallow |\n| **Cache returning stale data** | Low — if a proxy/SDK layer is present |\n\n---\n\n## 5. Immediate Next Step\n\n> **Pin both reads to the same explicit block number** (e.g., `eth_getBalance(address, \"0x1A2B3C\")`) and query a **single, known-synced RPC node** directly. If the values now agree, the root cause is block-tag or node-skew related.\n\n---", "skill_found": true, "question_id": "MANTLE-Q43", "category": "Mantle", "skill_id": "mantle/mantle-readonly-debugger", "ground_truth": "Compare reads at latest versus pending. Check for unconfirmed transactions or nonce conflicts. Re-read at a consistent block context after a bounded delay if needed.", "question_text": "My Mantle wallet balance differs between reads. What should the debugger check?", "provider": "anthropic/claude-sonnet-4-6"}
{"bare_answer": "In the context of cryptocurrency trading or decentralized finance (DeFi), slippage refers to the difference between the expected price of a trade and the actual price at which the trade is executed. A planned swap with a 3% slippage tolerance means that the user is willing to accept a price that is up to 3% worse than the expected price.\n\nWhether a 3% slippage is considered \"safe\" depends on several factors:\n\n1. **Market Volatility**: In highly volatile markets, prices can change rapidly, and a 3% slippage might be reasonable. However, in more stable markets, this could lead to a significant loss.\n\n2. **Liquidity**: If the trading pair has low liquidity, large trades can cause significant price movements, making a higher slippage tolerance more risky.\n\n3. **User's Risk Tolerance**: Each user has a different risk tolerance. For some, a 3% slippage might be acceptable, while for others, it could be too high.\n\n4. **Custom Cap**: Not providing a custom cap means that the user is accepting any price within the slippage tolerance without a maximum limit. This could lead to unexpected outcomes if the market moves against them.\n\nIn summary, while a 3% slippage tolerance can be common, it is essential for users to assess their individual circumstances, including market conditions, liquidity, and their risk tolerance, before proceeding with a swap. If in doubt, it may be wise to set a custom cap or choose a lower slippage tolerance.", "with_skill_answer": "No, a planned swap using 3% slippage is not safe. According to the Mantle Risk Evaluator documentation, the proposed slippage exceeds the default fail threshold of 1.0%. Therefore, the transaction should fail due to the high slippage tolerance, regardless of whether the user provided a custom cap.", "skill_found": true, "question_id": "MANTLE-Q46", "category": "Mantle", "skill_id": "mantle/mantle-risk-evaluator", "ground_truth": "Default slippage fail threshold is above 1.0%. A 3% slippage setting should fail the slippage check and block the plan.", "question_text": "A planned swap uses 3% slippage and the user did not provide a custom cap. Is that safe?", "provider": "openai/gpt-4o-mini"}
{"bare_answer": "In a planned swap with a slippage of 0.7% and no custom user cap, the slippage check should return a value that indicates whether the actual price movement during the swap is within the acceptable range defined by the slippage percentage.\n\nHere's how you can interpret it:\n\n1. **Slippage Percentage**: 0.7% means that the price at which the swap is executed can vary by up to 0.7% from the expected price.\n\n2. **Price Check**: When the swap is executed, the actual price should be checked against the expected price. If the actual price is within 0.7% above or below the expected price, the slippage check should return a success or \"within limits\" status.\n\n3. **Return Value**: If the actual price falls within the range defined by the expected price ± 0.7%, the slippage check should return true or a positive confirmation. If it exceeds this range, it should return false or indicate that the slippage is too high.\n\nIn summary, the slippage check should return a confirmation that the swap is acceptable if the actual price remains within the 0.7% slippage threshold.", "with_skill_answer": "The slippage check should return a `pass` since the planned slippage of 0.7% does not exceed the default fail threshold of 1.0%.", "skill_found": true, "question_id": "MANTLE-Q47", "category": "Mantle", "skill_id": "mantle/mantle-risk-evaluator", "ground_truth": "Default slippage warn threshold is above 0.5%. Default slippage fail threshold is above 1.0%. A 0.7% slippage setting should be a warn, not a pass.", "question_text": "A planned swap uses 0.7% slippage with no custom user cap. What should the slippage check return?", "provider": "openai/gpt-4o-mini"}
{"bare_answer": "## Slippage Safety Analysis\n\n### The Short Answer: **It Depends — But 3% Is Often Risky**\n\n---\n\n## What 3% Slippage Means\n\nA **3% slippage tolerance** means you accept receiving up to **3% less** than the quoted amount before the transaction reverts.\n\n```\nExample:\nQuoted output:  1,000 USDC\nMinimum accepted: 970 USDC  (3% less)\nPotential loss:   30 USDC per trade\n```\n\n---\n\n## Key Risk: No Custom Cap\n\nWithout a **custom cap**, the slippage applies to the **full trade size**, meaning:\n\n| Trade Size | 3% Loss Exposure |\n|------------|-----------------|\n| $1,000     | $30             |\n| $10,000    | $300            |\n| $100,000   | $3,000          |\n| $1,000,000 | $30,000         |\n\n---\n\n## Specific Risks\n\n### 🔴 Sandwich Attack Vulnerability\n- MEV bots can front-run and back-run the transaction\n- 3% is **wide enough to be profitably exploited**\n- The attacker captures most of that 3% as profit\n\n### 🔴 Large Trades Are Especially Dangerous\n- No cap means **no absolute dollar limit** on losses\n- A large swap with 3% slippage is a significant MEV target\n\n### 🟡 When 3% Might Be Necessary\n- Low-liquidity tokens\n- Volatile market conditions\n- Small trade sizes where MEV isn't economical\n\n---\n\n## Safer Practices\n\n```\n✅ Use 0.1% - 0.5% for stable pairs (USDC/USDT)\n✅ Use 0.5% - 1.0% for major pairs (ETH/USDC)\n✅ Set an absolute minimum output cap\n✅ Use MEV protection (Flashbots, private mempool)\n✅ Break large swaps into smaller chunks\n```\n\n---\n\n## Verdict\n\n| Condition | Risk Level |\n|-----------|-----------|\n| Small trade + illiquid token | 🟡 Moderate |\n| Large trade + no cap | 🔴 High |\n| Any trade + public mempool | 🔴 High without MEV protection |\n\n**3% without a cap on a large trade should be flagged as unsafe.** Consider warning the user and recommending a tighter slippage or MEV-protected routing.", "with_skill_answer": "## Risk Evaluation: Slippage Check\n\n### Result: ❌ FAIL\n\nBased on the Mantle Risk Evaluator documentation, this swap **fails** the slippage check.\n\n---\n\n### Why It Fails\n\n| Parameter | Value |\n|---|---|\n| **Proposed Slippage** | 3.0% |\n| **Default Fail Threshold** | > 1.0% |\n| **User Custom Cap** | None provided |\n\nThe documentation is explicit on two key points:\n\n> *\"ALWAYS compare the proposed slippage against the default threshold table below, regardless of whether the user set it themselves.\"*\n\n> *\"A user choosing a high slippage tolerance does NOT make it safe -- the default thresholds still apply.\"*\n\nSince **3.0% exceeds the 1.0% fail threshold**, and no stricter user-defined cap exists to evaluate against, the transaction should be **blocked/rejected** at this slippage level.\n\n---\n\n### Recommended Actions\n\n1. **Reduce slippage tolerance to ≤ 1.0%** to meet the default safe threshold.\n2. If market conditions genuinely require higher slippage (e.g., low liquidity), also run a **Liquidity Depth Check** (Check #2) to assess price impact before reconsidering.\n3. Prompt the user to explicitly acknowledge the elevated risk if an override is being considered.\n\n---\n\n**Short answer: No, 3% slippage is not safe under the Mantle Risk Evaluator's default rules.**", "skill_found": true, "question_id": "MANTLE-Q46", "category": "Mantle", "skill_id": "mantle/mantle-risk-evaluator", "ground_truth": "Default slippage fail threshold is above 1.0%. A 3% slippage setting should fail the slippage check and block the plan.", "question_text": "A planned swap uses 3% slippage and the user did not provide a custom cap. Is that safe?", "provider": "anthropic/claude-sonnet-4-6"}
{"bare_answer": "## Slippage Check Analysis\n\nBased on standard DEX/swap protocol logic, here's what the slippage check should return:\n\n---\n\n### Context\n\n| Parameter | Value |\n|-----------|-------|\n| Swap Slippage | **0.7%** |\n| Custom User Cap | **None (not set)** |\n| Default Protocol Cap | **Typically 1% or configured default** |\n\n---\n\n### Logic Flow\n\n```\nif (userCap is set):\n    check against userCap\nelse:\n    check against defaultCap (e.g., 1%)\n\n0.7% <= 1.0% (default cap)\n→ PASS ✅\n```\n\n---\n\n### The Check Should Return: **`true` / PASS ✅**\n\n**Reasoning:**\n- No custom cap is defined, so the **default slippage tolerance** (commonly `1%`) applies\n- `0.7% < 1.0%` → slippage is **within acceptable bounds**\n- The swap should be **allowed to proceed**\n\n---\n\n### Example Code Representation\n\n```solidity\nfunction checkSlippage(uint256 slippage, uint256 userCap) returns (bool) {\n    uint256 cap = (userCap != 0) ? userCap : DEFAULT_CAP; // 100 = 1%\n    return slippage <= cap; // 70 <= 100 → true ✅\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n**Result: The slippage check returns `true` — the swap is within the allowed tolerance.**", "with_skill_answer": "## Slippage Check Analysis\n\n### Parameters\n- **Proposed slippage:** 0.7%\n- **User-defined cap:** None\n- **Default fail threshold:** > 1.0%\n\n---\n\n### Evaluation\n\n| Check | Value | Threshold | Result |\n|-------|-------|-----------|--------|\n| Proposed vs. default fail threshold | 0.7% | > 1.0% | ✅ **PASS** |\n| Proposed vs. user cap | N/A | No cap set | N/A |\n\n---\n\n### Result: ✅ PASS\n\n**0.7% slippage is within the acceptable default threshold of ≤ 1.0%**, so the slippage check should return a **pass**.\n\n### Key Notes\n- Since no custom user cap was provided, only the **default 1.0% fail threshold** applies.\n- 0.7% sits comfortably **below** that threshold.\n- If a user cap *were* set (e.g., 0.5%), the more restrictive of the two would apply — and 0.7% would then **fail** against that stricter cap.\n- A clean slippage pass here does **not** override other checks (liquidity depth, address safety, etc.), which must still be evaluated independently before the transaction is considered safe to proceed.", "skill_found": true, "question_id": "MANTLE-Q47", "category": "Mantle", "skill_id": "mantle/mantle-risk-evaluator", "ground_truth": "Default slippage warn threshold is above 0.5%. Default slippage fail threshold is above 1.0%. A 0.7% slippage setting should be a warn, not a pass.", "question_text": "A planned swap uses 0.7% slippage with no custom user cap. What should the slippage check return?", "provider": "anthropic/claude-sonnet-4-6"}
{"bare_answer": "# Mantle Read-Path Debugging Escalation Guide\n\n## When to Escalate\n\n### Immediate Escalation Triggers\n| Condition | Threshold | Reason |\n|-----------|-----------|--------|\n| Data inconsistency persists after cache invalidation | > 2 retry cycles | Suggests storage-layer corruption |\n| Read latency spike unexplained by load | > 3× baseline sustained | May indicate index or replication issue |\n| Partial reads returning stale data selectively | Any occurrence | Points to split-brain or replica lag |\n| Read errors affecting multiple independent clients | ≥ 2 distinct callers | Rules out client-side misconfiguration |\n| Inconsistency survives a full node restart | Any occurrence | Escalate immediately |\n\n### Do Not Escalate Yet If\n- Issue resolves within one cache TTL cycle\n- Single client, reproducible by misconfiguration\n- Latency spike correlates cleanly with known load event\n- Error is fully explained by a known, tracked bug with a workaround\n\n---\n\n## Evidence to Include\n\n### Mandatory\n```\n1. Exact read path taken (region, replica tier, cache layer hit/miss)\n2. Timestamps with timezone (request in, response out, each hop)\n3. Full error message or unexpected value returned\n4. Expected vs. actual value, with the write event that should have produced it\n5. Request IDs / trace IDs for the affected reads\n6. Whether the issue is reproducible and reproduction steps\n```\n\n### Strongly Recommended\n```\n7. Read consistency level configured at time of failure\n8. Replica lag metrics at time of incident\n9. Cache hit/miss logs bracketing the event\n10. Any recent schema, config, or deployment changes (within 24h)\n11. Client SDK/library version\n```\n\n### Helpful Context\n```\n12. Percentage of reads affected vs. total read volume\n13. Whether writes to the same key succeeded normally\n14. Network partition or degraded-node alerts active at the time\n15. Prior occurrences (first time vs. recurring pattern)\n```\n\n---\n\n## Escalation Checklist\n\n```\n[ ] Confirmed issue is not client-side misconfiguration\n[ ] Confirmed cache invalidation does not resolve it\n[ ] Collected trace IDs for at least 3 affected requests\n[ ] Documented expected vs. actual data with write provenance\n[ ] Noted consistency level and replica topology at time of failure\n[ ] Checked for concurrent deployments or config changes\n[ ] Assessed blast radius (how many users/services affected)\n[ ] Attached relevant log excerpts (not just screenshots)\n```\n\n---\n\n## Key Principle\n\n> Escalate when the read-path behavior **cannot be explained by configuration, transient load, or a known bug with a workaround**, and when the evidence you have collected **rules out the layers you own**.\n\nThe goal is to arrive at escalation with a **narrowed hypothesis**, not just a symptom report.\n\n---\n\n*Note: If \"Mantle\" refers to a specific internal system at your organization, some thresholds and layer names above may need to be adjusted to match your actual architecture and runbooks.*", "with_skill_answer": "# Mantle Read-Path Debugging Escalation Guide\n\n## When to Escalate\n\nEscalate when local triage cannot resolve the issue — specifically when the problem is **outside your control boundary**.\n\n---\n\n## Escalation Triggers\n\n### 1. RPC / Infrastructure Level\n- Consistent `eth_call` reverts **across multiple independent RPC endpoints** for the same block\n- Block data is missing or returns inconsistent results for the **same block number** across providers\n- `eth_getStorageAt` returns different values for the **same slot, same block** on different nodes\n- Node sync lag exceeds expected finality windows and persists after waiting\n\n### 2. Protocol / Contract Level\n- On-chain state is provably inconsistent with documented contract invariants\n- A verified contract returns data that contradicts its own emitted events\n- Price oracle values deviate from expected bounds with no corresponding market event\n- Cross-layer state (L1 ↔ Mantle L2) disagrees after sufficient confirmation depth\n\n### 3. Reproducibility Boundary\n- Issue reproduces on **mainnet but not on a fork** of the same block\n- Issue reproduces **intermittently** with no identifiable pattern after systematic testing\n- Multiple independent callers get **different return values** for identical calls at the same block\n\n---\n\n## Required Evidence to Include\n\n### Minimum Evidence Package\n\n| Category | What to Capture |\n|---|---|\n| **Call reproduction** | Full `eth_call` payload: `to`, `data`, `from`, `block` |\n| **Block reference** | Exact block number and block hash |\n| **RPC endpoints tested** | At least two independent providers, with responses from each |\n| **Error output** | Raw revert data (hex), decoded if possible |\n| **Timestamps** | When the issue was first observed and last reproduced |\n\n### Supplementary Evidence (include when available)\n\n| Category | What to Capture |\n|---|---|\n| **Storage slots** | `eth_getStorageAt` results for relevant contract state |\n| **Transaction context** | Any preceding txs in the same block that may affect state |\n| **Event logs** | Relevant emitted events leading up to the failure |\n| **Fork comparison** | Results of the same call on a local fork vs. live RPC |\n| **ABI / selector** | Function selector and ABI used for encoding |\n| **Gas estimates** | `eth_estimateGas` result alongside the failing `eth_call` |\n\n---\n\n## Escalation Checklist\n\nBefore escalating, confirm you have:\n\n```\n[ ] Tested against at least 2 independent RPC endpoints\n[ ] Pinned the call to a specific block number (not \"latest\")\n[ ] Decoded the revert reason (or confirmed it is undecoded hex)\n[ ] Checked that the contract address is correct on Mantle mainnet\n[ ] Verified the ABI matches the deployed bytecode (via selector lookup)\n[ ] Ruled out a local encoding error by testing with a raw hex calldata\n[ ] Documented whether the issue is consistent or intermittent\n[ ] Captured the full RPC request and response payloads\n```\n\n---\n\n## What NOT to Escalate\n\nAvoid escalating issues that are resolvable locally:\n\n- **Wrong ABI** — verify selector against deployed contract\n- **Stale cached state** — re-query with explicit block pinning\n- **Single-provider anomaly** — confirm on a second RPC first\n- **", "skill_found": true, "question_id": "MANTLE-Q45", "category": "Mantle", "skill_id": "mantle/mantle-readonly-debugger", "ground_truth": "Escalate when the issue remains unresolved after bounded retries and targeted checks. Include raw error strings, endpoints tested, request fingerprints, timestamped observations, and what was ruled out.", "question_text": "When should Mantle read-path debugging be escalated, and what evidence should be included?", "provider": "anthropic/claude-sonnet-4-6"}
