ther libraries or frameworks being used in the project (e.g., ReactiveCocoa, Alamofire).\n\n10. **Documentation**:\n    - Include clear documentation on how to use the Mantle models, including examples of serialization/deserialization and any specific behaviors.\n\n11. **Versioning**:\n    - Consider how changes to the models will be versioned and how backward compatibility will be handled.\n\n12. **Memory Management**:\n    - Check for any potential memory leaks or retain cycles, especially when dealing with relationships.\n\nIncluding these checks in your development brief will help ensure that the integration of Mantle into your project is successful and that any potential issues are addressed early in the development process.", "with_skill_answer": "In the development brief for a Mantle project, the following Mantle-specific integration checks should be included:\n\n1. **MNT Gas and Operational Assumptions**: Outline the gas costs associated with transactions on the Mantle network and any operational considerations that may affect contract performance.\n\n2. **Environment-Correct Protocol/System Addresses**: Ensure that all protocol and system addresses used in the contract are correct for the target environment (mainnet or testnet).\n\n3. **Deployment Roles and Initialization Values**: Define the roles involved in the deployment process and the initial values required for the contract's constructor or initializer.\n\n4. **Integration Points Needed by Frontends or Offchain Services**: Identify any specific integration points that are necessary for front-end applications or off-chain services to interact with the smart contracts effectively.\n\nThese checks are crucial for ensuring that the smart contract functions correctly within the Mantle ecosystem and meets all operational requirements.", "skill_found": true, "question_id": "MANTLE-Q65", "category": "Mantle", "skill_id": "mantle/mantle-smart-contract-developer", "ground_truth": "Confirm MNT gas assumptions. 