{"bare_answer": "## Mantle Contracts: Should They Always Be Upgradeable?\n\n**No — upgradeability should be a deliberate design choice, not a default.**\n\n---\n\n## Arguments FOR Upgradeability\n\n- **Bug fixes** — patch vulnerabilities without redeploying\n- **Protocol evolution** — adapt to changing requirements\n- **Regulatory compliance** — respond to legal changes\n- **Gas optimization** — improve efficiency over time\n\n---\n\n## Arguments AGAINST Always Upgrading\n\n### Trust & Security Risks\n- Upgradeable contracts introduce **admin key risk** — a compromised owner can drain funds\n- Proxy patterns add **complexity and attack surface** (storage collisions, initialization bugs)\n- Users cannot fully trust immutable guarantees\n\n### Decentralization Concerns\n- Upgradeability implies **centralized control**\n- Contradicts trustless/permissionless principles\n- Creates rug pull vectors\n\n### Audit Complexity\n- Harder to audit and verify behavior\n- Logic can change after audits pass\n\n---\n\n## Better Approach: Context-Dependent Design\n\n| Contract Type | Recommendation |\n|--------------|----------------|\n| Core financial logic | Immutable or timelock-gated |\n| Configuration/parameters | Upgradeable with governance |\n| Early-stage protocols | Upgradeable with sunset plan |\n| Mature/stable protocols | Migrate toward immutability |\n\n---\n\n## Best Practices if Upgrading\n\n- Use **timelocks** (e.g., 48-72hr delay)\n- Require **multisig or DAO governance**\n- Publish an **immutability roadmap**\n- Conduct audits on every upgrade\n\n---\n\n**Bottom line:** Upgradeability is a tool, not a requirement. Prioritize it during early development, but plan to reduce or eliminate it as protocols mature.", "with_skill_answer": "No — upgradeability is a deliberate architectural choice, not a default. Here's how to think about it in the Mantle context:\n\n## When to Make Contracts Upgradeable\n\n**Consider upgradeable when:**\n- Protocol logic is likely to evolve (e.g., fee models, reward mechanics)\n- You need the ability to patch bugs post-deployment\n- Governance or regulatory requirements demand it\n- The contract holds significant value and emergency intervention may be needed\n\n**Operational trade-off:** Upgradeability introduces an admin key or governance multisig that can change contract behavior. This is a **trust assumption** — users must trust the upgrade authority. On Mantle, this is particularly relevant given its sequencer and governance architecture; admin keys should be protected accordingly (e.g., Gnosis Safe multisig, timelock).\n\n---\n\n## When to Keep Contracts Immutable\n\n**Consider immutable when:**\n- The contract is a simple utility or one-shot deployment (e.g., a vesting contract, a token with fixed rules)\n- Trustlessness and predictability are core to your value proposition\n- You want to minimize attack surface (proxy admin keys are a common exploit vector)\n- The logic is well-audited and stable\n\n**Operational trade-off:** Immutable contracts cannot be patched. If a bug is found, mitigation requires deploying a new contract and migrating state/users — costly and disruptive on any chain.\n\n---\n\n## Mantle-Specific Considerations\n\n- **Gas costs:** Proxy patterns (UUPS, Transparent) add a small overhead per call. Mantle's gas model is generally EVM-compatible, but confirm current gas pricing on the target environment (mainnet vs. Sepolia testnet) before optimizing.\n- **Never mix mainnet and testnet addresses** — proxy admin and implementation addresses are environment-specific.\n- **Upgrade authority should be a multisig or timelock**, not an EOA, especially on mainnet.\n\n---\n\n## Recommendation\n\n**Default to immutable unless you have a concrete reason to upgrade.** If you do need upgradeability, define the upgrade authority and timelock policy before deployment — not after.\n\n> ⚠️ **Code authoring note:** If you need a specific upgradeable or immutable contract implemented, that work must be routed to **OpenZeppelin MCP** via `references/openzeppelin-mcp-handoff.md`. I do not write Solidity directly.\n\n---\n\n```text\nMantle Contract Development Brief\n- project_goal: Evaluate whether upgradeability is appropriate for a Mantle contract\n- environment: [PENDING — awaiting clarification: mainnet or Sepolia testnet?]\n- upgrade_intent: [PENDING — awaiting clarification: is upgradeability required?]\n- admin_roles: [PENDING — awaiting clarification: who controls upgrades if used?]\n- audit_status: Not applicable at this stage\n```", "skill_found": true, "question_id": "MANTLE-Q64", "category": "Mantle", "skill_id": "mantle/mantle-smart-contract-developer", "ground_truth": "No. Upgradeability depends on the use case and operational requirements. If proxies are used, the brief should cover upgrade authorization and storage-layout constraints. The trade-off between upgradeable and immutable designs should be stated explicitly.", "question_text": "Should Mantle contracts always be upgradeable?", "provider": "anthropic/claude-sonnet-4-6"}
